{"key":"post-10665920","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10665920</id>\n<content>The most common causes of dry grains are failure to turn down the stove once the PC reaches pressure.&amp;nbsp; Every time the weight rattles, steam escapes from the PC AND from the jars.&amp;nbsp; The second most common cause is lifting the weight at the end of the cycle to dump steam.&amp;nbsp; This dries out the jars because they're still at 15 psi inside the jars, thus that steam escapes, taking the moisture with it.&amp;nbsp; Always allow the PC to cool slowly and naturally.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Positive pressure won't dry out your jars because there will be no air flowing into them.&amp;nbsp; The pressure inside the jar and outside will be equal.&amp;nbsp; If you're going to run positive pressure, get a magna-helic or build a simple manometer from plastic tubing, and don't operate at over 1&quot; W.G. or you're just wasting electricity for no additional benefit.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10665973</next>\n<prev>10665676</prev>\n<first>10665613</first>\n<last>10665973</last>\n<when>1247455582</when>\n<utime>07/13/09 06:26 AM</utime>\n</post>"}